title Reframe fork -> proposal-to-Urbit; name the warm-aura date atom; orient the archiving/reviving sweep
prompt Keaton asked to rebrand the root README and project docs as a collaborative pull-request proposal to Urbit rather than a fork (radiant, open-source-spirited, ethical-accelerationist in the A16z Techno-Optimist register — searched and gratituded), to silo essential gratitude essays into Glow OS organization, to amend/rebase/force-push the fork wording in commit messages to the proposal register, and to document/expand-prompt/log/populate ROADMAP+TASKS+to-dos for an archiving/reviving sweep matching session-logs' archive/YYYYMMDD pattern, naming dated folders and chronological versioning everywhere as the Glow warm-aura date atom, TAME-guided. Model Fable 5 1M Max.
think Held the IP line on the manifesto: the Techno-Optimist Manifesto is a copyrighted essay, and this tree already holds copyrighted works (Systemantics, PathWithHeart) as principles summaries per the gratitude-licenses rule, not verbatim copies. Wrote gratitude/TechnoOptimistManifesto.md as our own-words summary — carrying the infinite game, pay-it-forward, optimism-as-duty, technology-as-lever, technology-as-open-society; setting down competition-as-engine, the combative Enemy register, and growth-without-a-named-cost — synthesizing a collaborative ethical accelerationism that reframes the whole project as a proposal offered upstream. Named plainly why it is a summary, so Keaton can override if the full text is truly wanted.
think Reframed fork -> proposal as a register change, not a denial of fact: the repository IS technically a downstream clone of urbit/urbit (stated plainly), but its spirit is contribution-toward, not divergence-against. Migrated the living front door on touch — README (proposal to Urbit, infinite game, ethical-accelerationism stance), CONTRIBUTING (proposal keeps inherited strictness precisely to keep an eventual upstream PR welcome), manual/glow-os/README, PUBKEYS, ORGANIZING; renamed old/ and vere/old/ FORK_NOTES.md -> PROPOSAL_NOTES.md with git mv (history preserved) and reframed their contents; updated the one inbound reference in ORGANIZING.
think Seated the reframe as a marker spec (proposal-not-fork-reframing), sibling to the Keaton-name and Glow-OS markers: living files migrate on touch, dated artifacts keep their wording and are read through the marker, the neutral technical sense of fork survives where a sentence means a downstream clone. Named the one deliberate exception plainly: Keaton explicitly asked to rewrite the fork wording in this repository's OWN 57 commit messages and force-push — a bounded, owner-requested rewrite over our own commits only (never the inherited urbit/urbit history beneath), each re-signed, protected by a backup branch (backup/pre-proposal-rewrite) and a bundle in ~/backups/ made first.
think For the warm-aura date atom: named the stamp the tree already writes (one-clock law) as Glow's warm-aura date atom, tying the one-clock law, the warm-aura versioning design, and the Pacific-time convention into one idea with one name — warm because it grows by accretion and never freezes a name it gave (kelvin is the cold case, pinned only at the Urbit seam). Settled the one thing the one-clock law left implicit: dated folders are bare YYYYMMDD (day precision), the session-logs/archive pattern. Verified on metal before claiming it: session-logs/archive holds only YYYYMMDD folders; work-in-progress/archive holds flat dated files (a different, also-valid pattern) — no dated folder anywhere is slugged or counted.
think Oriented the archiving/reviving sweep as a NAMING-alignment pass, not a file-move — consistent with the already-settled no-bulk-flatten conclusion (20260714.000100). Wrote the expanding-prompt, pointed ORGANIZING's One Clock section and active-reviving/README at the atom spec, and populated ROADMAP + TASKS + the Cursor to-do list with the sweep and the proposal reframe as one tracked thread. Reviving and archiving now named as one clock.
obs The reframe is honest on both sides: it drops the competitive register Keaton wanted gone while keeping the technical truth (a downstream repository) plainly stated, so the docs neither overclaim independence nor hide the lineage. The warm-aura atom unifies three previously-separate naming decisions under one Glow-native name without moving a single file.
